File: `platform/browser-extension/src/side-panel/components/PluginCard.tsx`, lines 44-61.

Current code captures `originalTools` at the start of each handler, then rolls back to it on error. The race: toggle A captures state S0 → optimistic update to S1 → toggle B captures S1 → optimistic update to S2 → request A fails → rollback to S0, losing S2.

Fix: Add `const toggleCounter = useRef(0)` at the component level. In each handler:
```
const myVersion = ++toggleCounter.current;
// ... optimistic update ...
void serverRequest().catch(() => {
  if (toggleCounter.current === myVersion) {
    updatePluginTools(() => originalTools);
  }
  showToggleError('...');
});
```

Both `handleToggleAll` (line 44) and `handleToggleTool` (line 53) need the same fix.

File: `platform/browser-extension/src/browser-commands/interaction-commands.ts`, lines 196-230.

The `func` passed to `chrome.scripting.executeScript` creates a Promise with a `setInterval` callback. The interval body calls `document.querySelector(sel)` then `getComputedStyle(htmlEl)`. If the element is detached between these two calls, `getComputedStyle` can throw.

Wrap the interval body:
```
const poll = setInterval(() => {
  try {
    // existing logic: querySelector, getComputedStyle, visibility check
  } catch (err) {
    clearInterval(poll);
    resolve({ error: `Error checking element: ${err instanceof Error ? err.message : String(err)}` });
  }
}, pollMs);
```

This is a small, surgical change — only the interval callback body needs wrapping.
